    <!-- JavaScript for Countdown Timer -->
    <script>
        function updateCountdown() {
            const earthDay = new Date('April 22, 2024 00:00:00').getTime();
            const now = new Date().getTime();
            const difference = earthDay - now;

            // Time calculations for days, hours, minutes, and seconds
            const days = Math.floor(difference / (1000 * 60 * 60 * 24));
            const hours = Math.floor((difference % (1000 * 60 * 60 * 24)) / (1000 * 60 * 60));
            const minutes = Math.floor((difference % (1000 * 60 * 60)) / (1000 * 60));
            const seconds = Math.floor((difference % (1000 * 60)) / 1000);

            // Display the result in the element with id="timer"
            document.getElementById('timer').innerHTML = days + " Days " + hours + " Hours " 
            + minutes + " Minutes " + seconds + " Seconds ";

            // If the countdown is finished, write some text
            if (difference < 0) {
                clearInterval(x);
                document.getElementById('timer').innerHTML = "Earth Day is here!";
            }
        }

        // Update the countdown every 1 second
        let x = setInterval(updateCountdown, 1000);
    </script>

    <section id="about-earth-day">
        <h2>About Earth Day</h2>
        <p>Earth Day, celebrated every year on April 22nd, marks a global commitment to environmental protection and sustainability. It's a day when individuals, communities, and organizations around the world engage in activities to promote ecological awareness and take action towards preserving our planet.<br>
            Since its inception in 1970, Earth Day has grown into a worldwide movement, emphasizing the urgent need to address environmental issues such as climate change, pollution, and wildlife conservation.</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Climate Action</li>
            <li>Science and Education</li>
            <li>Conservation and Restoration</li>
        </ul>
        <ol>
            <li>Reduce</li>
            <li>Reuse</li>
            <li>Recycle</li>
        </ol>
        <dl>
            <dt>Carbon Footprint</dt>
            <dd>The total amount of greenhouse gases produced to directly and indirectly support human activities, typically expressed in equivalent tons of carbon dioxide (CO2).<br>
            This includes emissions from burning fossil fuels for electricity, heat, and transportation, as well as emissions from industries, agriculture, and deforestation. Reducing our carbon footprint is crucial in combating climate change, and it can be achieved through energy efficiency, adopting renewable energy sources, and changing consumption habits.</dd>
        </dl>
    </section>

